This is a subtle behavior that affects every file. Here's how a robust fix for this would look like:

extract this loop into a stand-alone function, put it in StrUtil.cpp.
add a few test cases for it in StrUtil_ut.cpp, for both cjk and non-cjk use cases, including a test that would fail with current code.
add a fix

It seems the issue with this code is that iswalnum relies on current locale, which is wrong.
If there's no built-in function that returns the right response, we should write one. It's just checking number ranges. So the current equivalent of iswalnum is roughly:
bool IsCharAlphaNum(c WCHAR) {
  if (c >= '0' && c <= '9') { return true;}
  if (c >= 'a' && c <= 'A') { return true;}
  if (c >= 'z' && c <= 'Z') { return true;}
  return false;
}

To add CJK support, we would add the case for CJK ranges.
I don't want to use windows-specific, locale-dependent implementation that I have no visibility into.

Personally, anything that reduces space for tabs is a negative for me.

~interesting that apps like firefox have other options such as move in addiion to a second quick click is close by default

@GitHubRulesOK: All those options such as Move, Size etc. are standard in the system menu, so nothing special in FF's case. Also, in FF (whether maximized or not) I can't even bring up the system menu with a left click and only Alt+Space does the trick. How are you managing "a second quick click [to] close by default" when even the first doesn't seem possible?

there is NO space to the left of my firefox v71x64 tabs (nor draging the space to right has any effect) possibly due to a customise options. Tabs are the second row down and it is the top title bar that has the program icon (firefox logo)

@GitHubRulesOK: Ok, so it does sound like you have some sort of customized setup because I haven't seen the traditional titlebar with app icon to the left in FF for years now. Perchance have you set browser.tabs.drawInTitlebar to false? For me personally that's just a waste of vertical screen space. Might as well use the titlebar for tabs as well. Anyway, if you have the FF icon showing up then of course it'll work the traditional way to bring up the system menu, and to close the app on double-clicking.
If this is replicated in Sumatra then I hope there'll be a way to toggle it in Advanced Settings also for those of us who don't like unnecessary space wastage. In any case I tend to run Sumatra maximized, so for me it's far simpler to just blindly toss the cursor to the top right corner of the screen and click once to close the app. That or good ol' Alt+F4 is far faster and easier any day IMO than seeking out the system menu icon to double-click in order to close the app.

